Title: Repetition
References: ŠTULAJTEROVÁ, A., JESENSKÁ, P.: English Stylistics. 1. vyd. Banská Bystrica : Univerzita Mateja Bela, 2013. 114 s.
Content:
Repetition is a literary device that repeats the same words or phrases a few times to make an idea clearer.

It creates a logical emphasis which is necessary to fix the attention of the reader on the key word of the sentence, particularly when the speaker is under the stress of strong emotion.

Types of repetition:

1. Anadiplosis - repetition of a word or words in successive clauses in such a way that the second clause starts with the same word which marks the end of the previous clause

·         When i give, I give myself.

2. Anaphora - repetition of words at the start of clauses or verses.

·         My life is my purpose. My life is my goal. My life is my inspiration.

3. Antistasis - repetition of words or phrases in opposite sense.

·         Why do so many people who can't write plays, write plays?

4. Diacope - repetition of words broken by some other words.

·         Born in a hotel room--and goddamn it--died in a hotel room.

5. Epanalepsis - repetition of same words at the end and start of a sentence

·         Music I heard with you was more than music, And bread I broke with you was more than bread.

6. Epimone - repetition of a phrase (usually a question) to stress a point.

7. Epiphora - repetition of the same word at the end of each clause.

·         Scarcity and want shall shun you, Ceres’ blessing so is on you.

8. Gradatio - a construction in poetry where the last word of one clause becomes the first of the next and so on.

·         Design must have had a designer. That designer must have been a person. That person is GOD.

9. Polyptoton - repetition of words of the same root with different endings.

10. Symploce - it is a combination of anaphora and epiphora in which repetition is both at the end and at the beginning.
